values: I'll be making a post on the LOTR trilogy day tomorrow but for today besides wishing those who celebrate it, Happy Easter,and thanking for the on the spot beta, here's 7 The forest was almost in darkness. Elijah was afraid to move away from the trail in case he lost his way, but on the trail itself there was no shelter. Yet if he found some, and stayed there, would he be overtaken in the night? Wake up to the smell of Uruk breath in his face ? Elijah tried to think of the Two Towers. The Orcs and Uruk-hai had camped overnight. Maybe they'd do the same here. Who was to say Peter hadn't got it right? "Fuck, this creatures aren't supposed to exist." he muttered. He'd go on for as long as he could and only stop when there was no other alternative. He plodded on thinking of what he could be doing instead. Eating at Fidel's. Going to the Cuba Bar with Dom. Enjoying Wellington with Dom. Dom...oh god. He tried to stop thinking and concentrated on what lay around him. Trees. All looking the same, all faintly menacing in the twilight. The forest seemed vast, and he had no survival skills at all. At least the trail was well marked and with any luck he'd be able to stick to it until the promised rescue. There again, the patrol leader could have been lying, and they'd all be feasting at Edoras, laughing at the stupid fool who believed he could last out here as a member of the Rohirrim. It was easy in this place to think thoughts that were miserable and dark. Thoughts that could feed the fear that was never that far away. He hated feeling like that. All his life he'd been taught to tackle his fears head on. If there was a part he was apprehensive about, go for it. If there was something he wanted to do, do it. How else would he ever know his own limits? It had helped him when he sent in that audition tape for Frodo. It would probably help him again when he got back...if he got back. Thing was, he'd never done any of it alone. Yes, his talent - and he still felt uncomfortable thinking he might be talented - that was his alone, but his support network was always there. Family, close friends, friends he'd made along the way - all had helped him but now...now there was no-one. He was alone. If he dwelled on it too long, it was a really terrifying thought. He laughed to himself at the worries he'd had coming to NZ. They seemed so small now. He'd been so excited, but in the darkness of his bedroom, had been privately scared. Everything would be so new. He'd have to rely on himself more than ever before. Yet, he'd done it. Made friends, new friends that now seemed family - and some more than family. More than brother. He never felt alone with Dom, he felt wanted and knew that Dom liked him as much as Elijah liked Dom. shut the fuck up, can't think like this He tried to remember what Dom's arms felt like. Tried to remember Dom's voice, and the way he whispered jokes to try and make Elijah laugh, if he was being too serious. He stumbled and almost fell. His face was wet...and he couldn't see at all for the mist across his eyes. He scrubbed them furiously with the edge of his cloak. You stupid fuck! Reliving what you can't have. You are bait. That's all you are, so get over yourself! He couldn't afford the luxury of thinking about Dom now. If he did he'd end up howling with the sheer overwhelming hopelessness he was trying to keep down. He had to keep going and survive this. Somehow he had to get to Edoras. Although, if he didn't rest soon, he'd fall asleep where he stood, right in the middle of the trail. There had to be someplace he could hide and rest. Something caught his eye as he passed, and he retraced his steps. When there was a gap in the forest canopy, and when the cloud cover parted, the moonlight shone on the trail. It broke the monotony of walking and Elijah had used it as a way of motivating himself. Moving from one patch of light to another before it faded, counting steps in between, anything to keep him going. Now he could see it shining onto a small clearing surrounded by fallen trees. He could avoid the clearing but the trees could give shelter, and it wasn't too far from the trail. Hurriedly, he made for it, before his legs stopped working all together. He slipped, slithered, and was so noisy at times he winced. He tried hard to place his feet carefully on what he thought was solid ground, but the moonlight wasn't constant, and he couldn't stand in the one spot waiting for it to return. The crack of twigs and the gasps he made as he slipped must have advertised his presence to the whole fucking world. He despised himself for his lack of skill. Finally he bumped into a fallen tree, scraping knees and shins even through the cloth trousers of the Rohan. He cursed, for the thousandth time that night, the deity that thought it was somehow amusing to put Elijah Wood, American actor, into a scenario like this. Obviously this deity didn't know what acting meant - as in 'not fucking real'. He slid down onto soft earth, resting his back against the tree. The smell of leaf mould and rotting bark was all around. There was a dip in the earth and he wondered if he could rest there. He could feel sleep coming and surely he'd be safe if he covered himself with leaves? He began to have doubts, remembering the leaders concern about being tracked. Maybe this was not a great idea...but he couldn't get up...he was exhausted. He lay down in the dip, covered himself with his cloak and scooped up leaves to try and blur the edges between man and plantlife. After a while he stopped caring whether he could be seen or not. He didn't even mind when something crept across his face. Alien bugs were the least of his worries... ****** Dom was stunned how easily humans could be tracked. Even he could smell them - the horses, the men and their apprehension. I am Uruk-hai. I am created to hunt them. He shuddered as he felt a surge of pride in the knowledge rise, then wane. Sometimes, the human that he once was became overwhelmed by the Uruk-hai he'd now become. He needed to be with humans again. It was horrific to think that if he stayed like this, he would lose his humanity. "Here they gathered..." An Orc was jabbering with the excitement of a soon-to be-found kill, but Dom could not disagree with him. The tracks and mingled scents did not lie. Dom could smell much more than apprehension. There was real fear here. It was pungent in his nostrils. His stomach clenched with the thrill and knowledge of what was to come. His cock pressed hard against his stomach, rigid with pleasure. The terror in the eyes, the lust to kill and obliterate the light. It was what he was made for, all he was made for. He gasped at the blackness of his thoughts. Fuck, he couldn't stop himself. He was planning to sabotage the kill before it started. What if he couldn't? What if he wanted this? He hurriedly examined the tracks, his night vision excellent. "They divided. Riders that way, then a walker." There was a sense of disappointment that the immediate kill would not be large. Horses and men would have meant a battle, a berserk rage to mutilate and destroy, but a walker was more certain. A definite victory. "We will eat tonight! " The Orcs crowed with delight. Dom hoped the man had been wounded. Hopefully he'd be dead by the time they reached him. A noble sacrifice to help his friends escape. For a brief minute he wondered how he was going to cope with this. Birds and animals were one thing but he was no fucking cannibal. He could too easily picture an Uruk feasting on a man...only not when the Uruk was him. How could he convince the Orcs he wasn't hungry? That the killing was enough? The Orcs wouldn't fall for it. They'd be as suspicious as hell. An Orc handed him a mangled brooch with threads of material still attached. He brought it to his nose. The same scent as on the piece of cloak he held tucked inside his uniform. Dom walked along the trail and this scent was the strongest with fear threaded through it, more and more powerfully. Elijah was the walker, the sacrifice to save the others. In that moment, Dom was more fully human than he thought possible. He wanted to scream at the unfairness of whatever fate was responsible for this. He was never going to be able to protect Elijah from being hunted. He'd have to watch him die horribly, and there was no way out, and nothing he could do and... He thrust his knife into his hand, the pain stopping the cycle of panic before it could take hold. Black blood welled up from the cut and dripped from his hand. The Orcs stared at him, until he daubed it like war paint across his face. That was a gesture they understood too well. Dear God, this had to be thought out carefully. He couldn't have his Orcs piling in there for the kill. He'd have to orchestrate it somehow. Yeah, how are you going to kill six fucking Orcs? He smiled. He was such an idiot. He was Uruk-hai. If he was angry enough he could kill them with his bare hands. He'd have to control himself, though. He needed the element of surprise. He wasn't the one the Orcs had to be wary of. Oh no, they couldn't suspect a thing. Yet he couldn't get carried away by the joy of killing, no matter how tempting it was. He couldn't be blinded by blood so that he turned on Elijah as well. A sudden vision filled his mind. A battered body, unrecognizable, with torn limbs scattered to slavering mouths. He gasped for breath, hiding his discomfort, pretending to look at tracks. He could not become so Uruk-hai that he murdered the one person who mattered to him the most. It would not be allowed to happen. It was unthinkable that it should happen. Silently and relentlessly the Orcs resumed their search. For the first time since he came to this place, Dom hoped against hope they would not find Elijah. ******* Elijah woke up suddenly, heart hammering. There was a sound of snuffling, undergrowth disturbed, twigs cracking. He held his breath trying to think of what to do but his body betrayed him. He couldn't seem to find the energy to sit up, never mind run. He listened further, wishing he had some sort of super sense that could give form to the dark shapes out there. Then all was silent again only...it wasn't. If Elijah listened, he could hear noises. Small animals, he hoped. Night birds. Things that didn't want to decorate their nests with his insides. He'd never been the camping type. Viggo had tried to persuade him, but Elijah had let it be known that roughing it on set was necessary - part of his job, but off set? He wanted a shower, his music, time out with mates. Although, when some of those on the Rohan shoots came back with stories of laughter under the stars, he'd felt jealous he'd not been able to share the experience. When he came face to face with Viggo again, he was going to tell him what he thought of life in the raw. It sucked. Really, really sucked. Even with the thick cloak he was chilled, his body was stiff and aching, he couldn't get comfortable, his stomach was past the point of complaining about the lack of food...the recital of all his complaints made him want to laugh out loud. He turned and the noise he made amongst the leaves and moss seemed impossibly loud. He prayed then. A silly, childish prayer. Now I lay me down to sleep... He felt ashamed, then, because he hadn't done that in a while. He closed his eyes and hoped Someone Out There would accept it was an emergency, and he really wanted his soul to be kept inside his body,thank you. And then he was asleep, and he didn't even care. ****** They carried on tracking. Dom watched the Orcs' strange, lolloping gait with interest. He let them do all the work for, after all, they were good at it. He kept trying to work out what Elijah might do, and as each fresh clue was eagerly taken up, he realised how easy this was. Clue was piling upon clue, and within shorter and shorter distances. Branches broken and ferns crushed, soft earth pressed into a distinctive shape as Elijah hurried along. Yet he was tiring and making more mistakes. He might as well have shouted 'Here I am' to the world. Where will you go to sleep? Dom prayed Elijah would have the sense to find some cover and give himself a chance of resting for a while. Somewhere safer than this trail, where every clue was a direction, and each moment showed Elijah was tiring, and making mistakes. He watched the Orcs become more excited as the evidence of Elijah's presence grew. He'd have to take more control of this. He warned them off. "The kill is mine. Mine to make and mine to share." There were the usual complaints, comments about Orcs doing all the work, and Uruks acting like masters, but these were followed by a few well-placed blows that made sure those complaints stopped very quickly. How dare they argue over a kill? He knew it was a mistake to set an Uruk over Orcs. Orc scum needed to stay with their own. Uruks knew their place in the scheme of things. He'd have to watch these warg turds. "The kill is mine." He wasn't having ANY argument with that. With sickening awareness, he realised he was treating Elijah like any Uruk would treat a human. Elijah was a target. Sport. Food. The pleasure of the kill was all that mattered, and the kill was Elijah. He tried to take hold of his memories of what he once was..of what they had shared, but they kept scattering. He stopped, breathing in deeply the scent of forest and mould. My Uruk-hai. My fighting Uruk-hai There had been something in the back of his mind for as long as he'd been conscious. A prickling, a hazy awareness of Other When he was concentrating on what he had to do, whether it was to do with Orcs or Elijah, it faded, but now he was quiet and thoughtful, and the words entered his mind as clear as day. They were not his thoughts or memories, but that didn't matter. He recognised them, responded to them with a surge of fierce obedience, My Lord He cried out then, not knowing what was happening. The Orcs stared at him, their eyes narrowing at the sign of weakness. He growled in fury and picked up part of a broken tree trunk. He hurled it across the trail, the effort making it travel some distance before it smashed against a tree. The strange thoughts vanished as if they had never been. His head ached. He must not lose his humanity, not this close to finding Elijah. Finding Elijah, unfortunately came quicker than he expected. The scent of weariness and fear strong under the rotting leaves at the base of a fallen and moss-covered tree. No, please God, no, let it be something else... Yet he knew, as the Orcs whispered, and hissed their discontent at having to wait before the kill, that they had found what they were looking for, and only their fear of him kept Elijah alive. Dom motioned them back. "We make camp there," he pointed to the other side of the trail. "You"...he nodded to one of the more biddable ones. "Guard this piece of man-flesh well. Touch him, and we feast on you, instead." The Orc muttered darkly, but took up a position on a mouldy stump, waiting for anything that moved. The others were not so convinced. They edged closer, trying his patience, testing him. "Why waste time? Why can't we have him now?" Dom thought frantically of something to say. He wished someone would press a hastily scribbled piece of paper on him right now. He'd never complain about rewrites again. He tried to remember The Two Towers. How would the scriptwriters do this? It came to him. "We kill at daybreak! In the dark, how can we see the fear? We need time for the knowledge of death to sweeten this one. We will eat manflesh for breakfast!" It sounded so fucking ridiculous. Yet the Orcs must have been impressed, for his words were accepted, and they settled down for the night on the other side of the trail, discussing what part of the human they wanted for themselves. Dom tried not to listen, patrolling the edge of the camp, always keeping an eye on the Orc on the tree stump whenever there was a gap in the foliage. There'd be no sleep for Dom or the Orc tonight. He couldn't take the risk of any of them getting too curious, or of Elijah waking up before the dawn. He had no plan worked out. No scheme that would mean escape when morning came. Elijah was going to die in the morning unless a miracle came their way.
